Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up early. He hated it especially because he was responsible for waking up everyone in his company. Quietly, he stood up from his bunk, put on his combat suit, threw on his flak jacket, and took his belongings out of the locker, handling a certain small box with care. He slung his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Everything he needed was attached, like his gas mask or his special glasses. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He pulled a lighter out of one jacket pocket and a cigarette out of the other. He lit it and took a short drag before opening the door slightly. In the past week, he had to come up with all sorts of things to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the pre-set alarm, as it usually didn't work and only a faint humming came from the speakers.
“Wake them up?” Cohren turned around and saw platoon leader Nemic approaching him.
"Yes", replied Cohren.
"With what do you want to try it this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came out to him already in full uniform.
"Good morning", said Craith.
"What woke you up then?", asked Cohren.
"So, first of all, we didn't feel like waiting to see what you come up with today again. And secondly, the shock troops, who are the first to get up, can choose the morning ration," replied one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, Sergeant," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. In the barracks a loud, shrill alarm sounded. Inside he heard muffled curses and people running around.
"Man, Valturi," said Nemic. "You'd think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
"Well, my people from the training camp have learned," Cohren replied, pointing to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and squad leaders also know that they have to get up before their units."
A few seconds later the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal items to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, others rather annoyed.
“Good morning,” said Cohren in a cheerful mood.
“With all due respect, Sir, why must you wake us up like this?” asked a Sergeant of the Shock Troops.
“Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn’t sleep,” said Cohren.
“Pack all your personal items,” Cohren continued. As a Lieutenant Colonel and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting it, along with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. “We’re not coming back here. Sergeants and Lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack the daily rations.”
The members of the Exodus Company scattered quickly. They were part of the 2nd Shock Troop Division, 2nd Army. Before they were merged, there were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was divided, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to Lieutenant Colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first squad, walked side by side under the light of many generator-powered lamps of the advanced deployment base. Most had red-tinted glass to avoid being detected by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and on the ground to combat them.
“A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds”, said Nemic with a dry laugh. “Where are they sending us?”
“An advanced deployment base outside of Ianlos. We will support the ground attack”, replied Cohren and took a drag on his cigarette. He gave Craith a share of the blame for starting him smoking, but a year in combat changes a person, so he said nothing.
“Shit. It’s getting worse on the front”, muttered Nemic. “All the news reports are saying: ‘Support the war efforts. Send aid to the Kurgan Front.’ How about sending some aid to the Howland Front?”
“Amen, brother”, said Cohren and flicked the remains of his cigarette into the mud. “At least we’re starting with the first armed squad and don’t have to run. Captain Shaw should be there by now.”
“Shaw has made a ride-sharing arrangement clear for us?” asked Nemic a bit surprised.
“Yes. He’s not as bad as I thought he’d be. Not particularly approachable, but you can get along with him.”
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger towards his larynx microphone while putting on his backpack. “All units of the Exodus Company will meet at the West Vehicle Park when they’re finished. We’ll leave with the first armed squad at 0500.”
The response from the squad leaders came in quick succession. Harris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all got here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth, and Cohren felt like he'd known them for ages, even though it had been at most two years. They were squad leaders, with Craith leading the second squad for a week now, after the previous leader was medically discharged after being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On their way to the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos combat tanks and four infantry fighting vehicles. Their crews were busy making sure their machines were ready for action. Quickly, Cohren spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was talking to the commander of the armed squad. As they approached, Shaw looked their way and came over to them, as always with a face that didn’t give anything away.
“Lieutenant Nemic… Lieutenant Valturi…”, he said, looking at Cohren's holster and then back up at him. “The company is ready, I assume?”
